<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="26" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="27.[192,1440,674,762]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,302,674,698]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">Ecology</emphasis>
. Lowland, montane. Epigean. Banks and beds of rivers and brooks, at a certain distance (
<quantity metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="26" unit="m" value="1.0" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="0.0">0–2 m</quantity>
) from water. Open ground; wet, gravelly, bare soil. Nocturnal; hides during the day deep among gravel and under stones as well as around their edges. Gregarious.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[192,1441,801,858]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,297,801,825]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">Biology</emphasis>
. Seasonality: September, November–March, June. Tenerals: January–March. Occasionally infested with fungi (Laboulbeniales). Defence mechanism: when alarmed, the adult escapes by running.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[192,1440,897,954]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,419,897,922]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">Dispersal power</emphasis>
. Macropterous, probably capable of flight. Fast runner. Vagility likely favoured by flight capacity.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[192,896,993,1018]" box="[192,896,993,1018]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,493,993,1017]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">Collecting techniques</emphasis>
. Raking the soil; turning stones.
</paragraph>
